english:
  title: Dedicatory Address for the New Foundation of Yongbowon Temple
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Great endeavors need not follow ancient precedent; what matters is the wisdom to adapt to changing times. Even the restoration of an old temple earns the Buddha's blessings—how much more so the founding of a new one?

    Consider the strategic crossroads near the capital, a vital junction in the southern reaches, isolated from settled lands. It has become a haunt of bandits and brigands. All the goods carried by beast and borne by man—the lifeblood of both state and household—must cross mountain and water from distant places. Yet when merchants approach the capital's gates, their cargo is seized by thieves. Not only are possessions lost; travelers themselves fall to violence. Hearing of this suffering, our heart grieves. A remedy is needed.

    Thus we establish a monastery here, that human voices might never cease, that this desolate place become a field of blessing under the Buddha's protection. With monks as guides and teachers, we awaken in all who come the aspiration for enlightenment. We build clustered halls for the sangha to dwell, endow fertile fields to sustain their needs, and grant the surrounding villages to support their operations. All is accomplished through private devotion, without drawing upon the state's coffers.

    Now the work nears completion, and we prepare the dedication ceremony. To illuminate the pure roots of Vairocana Buddha, none surpasses the sublime teachings of Li Changzhe. Before this gathering, though nine lecture series have already been expounded, our original wish is to continue through ten. We have invited a hundred eminent monks from the southern provinces to expound the dharma of perfect penetration, blessing all beings throughout the cosmos.

    May this noble cause be reflected in heaven's mirror. We humbly pray: may the state's foundation stand firm as the Nine Tripods, may the sovereign's fortune extend beyond the ages. May public and private prosperity flourish until no lost coin lies upon the road, and may all lands know such peace that warfare becomes unknown to our people.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Li Changzhe (李長者, 7th-8th century): A celebrated Buddhist scholar and commentator on the Huayan Sutra, highly respected in East Asian Buddhism.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Nine Tripods: A metaphorical reference to stable, enduring imperial rule, drawn from Chinese dynastic symbolism.'
  - key: ''
    value: The text addresses a practical problem—the monastery serves both spiritual and defensive purposes, protecting merchants and travelers from bandits while establishing a center of Buddhist learning.
